  <div class="detail-info">
    <p class="detail-label">tabletop</p>
    <h1 class="detail-name">Kubus Candleholder</h1>
    <p class="detail-material">architectural steel design</p>
    <hr class="detail-divider">
    <p class="detail-story">Designed by <strong>Mogens Lassen</strong> in 1962, the Kubus is a study in structural honesty. Four candle spires rise from an open steel cube — the geometry does all the work, nothing is decorative that isn't also structural.</p>
    <p class="detail-story">Lassen was an architect, and it shows. The Kubus reads differently depending on whether the candles are lit or not — two distinct objects sharing one form. Produced today by <strong>by Lassen</strong> in Denmark, faithful to the original drawings.</p>
    <p class="detail-why">selected because it is equally at home on a dining table or a mantle — and it looks as good empty as it does in use.</p>
    <hr class="detail-divider">
    <div class="detail-meta">
      <div><p class="meta-label">designer</p><p class="meta-value">Mogens Lassen, 1962</p></div>
      <div><p class="meta-label">materials</p><p class="meta-value">powder-coated steel</p></div>
      <div><p class="meta-label">origin</p><p class="meta-value">Denmark</p></div>
      <div><p class="meta-label">made for</p><p class="meta-value">dining table, mantle, display</p></div>
    </div>
